---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Teachers | 7-Day Phật Thất Retreat at Bodh Gaya">
    <section class="max-w-4xl py-16 space-y-10">
        <div>
            <p class="mb-3 text-sm tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-neutral-500">Sangha</p>
            <h1 class="mb-6">Retreat Leadership</h1>
            <p class="max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                The 7-Day Phật Thất Retreat in Bodh Gaya, India, will be held with the presence and spiritual witness of Most Venenrable Thích Như Điển, the
                Abbot of Viên Giác Root Monastery, and will be guided by monastics from Viên Giác and its affiliated monasteries in Europe, including Amitayus
                Monastery, Liên Tâm Monastery, and Viên Lạc Retreat Center.
            </p>
            <p class="max-w-3xl mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                Viên Giác Root Monastery belongs to the Lâm Tế Chúc Thánh lineage, a branch of the Linji tradition, and takes the integrated practice of Chan
                and Pure Land as its foundation. On that basis, the dharma masters have also studied other Buddhist traditions in order to enrich both the path
                of practice and the way they guide practitioners.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid gap-6">
            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="space-y-8">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/hoathuongthichnhudien.png" alt="Hòa Thượng Thích Như Điển" class="h-[460px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Most Venerable Thích Như Điển</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">
                            Founder of Viên Giác Root Monastery, Hannover – Germany<br />
                            Second President of the Unified Vietnamese Buddhist Congregation in Europe<br />
                            Vice President of the World Buddhist Sangha Council (WBSC)
                        </p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Most Venerable Thích Như Điển, Dharma name Giải Minh and Dharma title Trí Tâm, was born in 1949 and is one of the most senior and
                            influential Vietnamese Buddhist teachers in Europe. After a solid monastic formation in Vietnam, he received novice ordination in
                            1967 and full bhikshu ordination in 1971. He later went to Japan for higher studies in education and Buddhist studies. In the late
                            1970s, Hòa Thượng came to Germany and began laying the foundation for Vietnamese Buddhist life there. In 1978, he established Viên
                            Giác in Hannover, which gradually grew into one of the most important Vietnamese Buddhist centers abroad.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Over several decades, Hòa Thượng has devoted himself to teaching, guiding monastics and lay practitioners, building Buddhist
                            institutions, and supporting the transmission of the Dharma throughout Europe. Under his leadership, Viên Giác became a major
                            religious and cultural center, welcoming tens of thousands of visitors each year.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            He has also ordained and trained 45 monastic disciples, played an important role in Vietnamese Buddhist organizations in Germany and
                            Europe, and authored and translated many Buddhist works. His long experience in teaching, leadership, and Dharma propagation
                            continues to inspire generations of practitioners.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">Hòa Thượng is a Dharma heir of the 41st generation of the Lâm Tế lineage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhtan.png" alt="Thầy Hạnh Tấn" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Venerable Thích Hạnh Tấn</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">Amitayus Monastery, Dippoldiswalde – Germany</p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Tấn was born in 1964 in Vietnam and arrived in Germany in 1979 as a refugee. After finishing secondary school, he entered
                            monastic training at Viên Giác Monastery in Hannover in 1986 and received novice ordination in 1987. In 1993, he received full
                            bhikshu ordination, completed graduate studies in Religious Studies, and then left Germany for India to deepen his Buddhist studies
                            and practice. In 2000, he returned to Germany, and three years later he was formally appointed abbot of Viên Giác Monastery in
                            Hannover. In 2008, he stepped down from that role in order to return to Asia with the aspiration for long-term retreat practice. In
                            2010, he returned to Germany and founded Amitayus Monastery near Dresden, where he now serves as abbot.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Tấn belongs to a newer generation of monastics who have received both a Western academic education and solid training in
                            their own Buddhist tradition, in this case Vietnamese and Chinese Mahāyāna Buddhism. In addition, he has studied and practiced
                            methods from other traditions as well, including Satipaṭṭhāna and Vipassanā from Thailand and Myanmar. The principal path he has
                            pursued most deeply, however, is Tibetan Vajrayāna.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">He is a Dharma heir of the 42nd generation of the Lâm Tế lineage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhbao.jpg" alt="Thầy Hạnh Bảo" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Venerable Thích Hạnh Bảo</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">
                            Abbot of Liên Tâm Monastery, Turku – Finland, and Viên Ý Pagoda – Italy; Executive Committee Member of the World Buddhist Sangha
                            Council (WBSC)
                        </p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Bảo was born in 1963 in Vietnam. He came to Germany for study while still young and later entered Viên Giác Monastery,
                            formally becoming a monk in 1991. He received novice ordination in 1991 and full bhikshu ordination in 1994.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            He is a well-known Dharma teacher who has taught widely to Vietnamese communities in Vietnam, the United States, South Korea, and
                            Europe. His study and Dharma work are rooted mainly in the Vietnamese Buddhist tradition, especially Pure Land practice and applied
                            Buddhism. His teaching style emphasizes Pure Land practice, scriptural study, and the application of Dharma in ordinary daily life.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            He is currently the abbot of Liên Tâm Monastery in Turku, Finland, and Viên Ý Pagoda in Italy. He also previously served as abbot of
                            Vạn Hạnh Pagoda in Denmark for ten years.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Since 2002, he has been an elected member of the Executive Committee of the World Buddhist Sangha Council.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">He is a Dharma heir of the 42nd generation of the Lâm Tế lineage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhdinh.jpg" alt="Thầy Hạnh Định" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Venerable Thích Hạnh Định</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">
                            Abbot of Phật Linh Pagoda, Bà Rịa–Vũng Tàu – Vietnam, and current abbot of Viên Giác Root Monastery, Hannover – Germany
                        </p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Định was born in 1972. After a period of Buddhist study and practice in Norway, where he had taken refuge with Hòa thượng
                            Thích Trí Minh at Khuông Việt Pagoda, he entered monastic life at Viên Giác Monastery in Hannover in 1997. He received novice
                            ordination in 1998 and full bhikshu ordination in 2001. In 2003, he was sent to India to serve at the Viên Giác Study Center while
                            also supporting Buddhist activities connected with Phật Linh Pagoda in Vietnam.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In 2006, he returned to Vietnam to directly supervise the restoration of Phật Linh Pagoda; the project was completed after four
                            years and formally inaugurated in 2009. Since then, he has continued to develop its practice life with the aspiration of building a
                            Pure Land practice center for the wider community. He currently also serves as abbot of Viên Giác Root Monastery in Hannover,
                            continuing the transmission and administration of the root monastery in Europe.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">He is a Dharma heir of the 42nd generation of the Lâm Tế lineage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div class="grid gap-8 md:grid-cols-[260px_1fr] md:items-start">
                    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-3xl border border-neutral-200 bg-white shadow-sm">
                        <img src="/images/thayhanhgioi.jpg" alt="Thầy Hạnh Giới" class="h-[320px] w-full object-cover object-top" />
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Venerable Thích Hạnh Giới</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">Abbot of Viên Lạc Retreat Center, Varel – Germany</p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            Thầy Hạnh Giới was born in 1971 in Vietnam. He entered monastic life in 1999, received novice ordination in 2000, and full bhikshu
                            ordination in 2002.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In terms of academic study, he pursued Religious Studies at the University of Hannover, Germany, where he completed a doctoral
                            degree. Alongside his academic formation, he has also devoted himself deeply to Chan practice and trained under the guidance of the
                            late Most Venerable Sheng-yen, founder of Dharma Drum Mountain in Taiwan.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            From 2008 to 2017, he served as the second abbot of Viên Giác Monastery. Since 2017, he has been the founding abbot of Viên Lạc
                            Retreat Center, an international center for Buddhist study, meditation, and retreat practice.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            His Dharma work includes teaching, guiding meditation, and giving talks in Vietnamese, German, English, and French throughout
                            Europe. His guidance focuses especially on Chan, Silent Illumination, mindfulness and breath meditation, Pure Land practice in the
                            spirit of Avataṃsaka-Chan, and the integration of meditation, compassion, and wisdom into daily life. Through retreats, Dharma
                            talks, and international programs, he supports practitioners from many countries in deepening meditation practice and bringing the
                            Buddha’s teachings into everyday life.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">He is a Dharma heir of the 42nd generation of the Lâm Tế lineage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>

            <article class="rounded-2xl border border-neutral-200 bg-neutral-50 p-6">
                <div>
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="mb-2">Other Members of the Sangha</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4 text-neutral-500">Supporting and organizing the retreat</p>
                        <p class="leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In addition to the main guiding teachers, the retreat is also supported by other members of the Sangha. Thầy Thông Tuệ, Thầy Thông
                            Kiên, and Sư Cô Thông Chu are the main monastics responsible for communication and coordination of the retreat. They also support
                            participants during the preparation period as well as throughout the retreat itself.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            In addition, there may be other Dharma teachers and Sangha members whose participation has not yet been confirmed. More information
                            will be added in the coming months.
                        </p>
                        <p class="mt-4 leading-8 text-neutral-700">
                            For more information about the monasteries and dharma teachers, visit: <a href="https://viengiac.info">viengiac.info</a>,
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</Layout>
